apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 CALAPAN, Philippines (AP) Hundreds of people who survived a typhoon in their seaside villages last month gave up and fled the area Tuesday after a strong earthquake and a tidal wave destroyed everything they had left on their central Philippine island. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Carrying bags of food and clothing on their heads and shoulders, at least 450 people walked down tar roads with huge cracks left in them by the quake that struck before dawn. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 At least 45 people were killed on the northern coast of Mindoro Island, 135 injured and eight left missing, and as many as 200 homes were destroyed, said Rodolfo Valencia, one of its two governors. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Most of the deaths came in the 3-foot (one-meter)-tall tidal wave. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Yuji Murata, 41, a scientist studying orchids for the Japanese government, was trapped by landslides along with three Filipino guides on a 5,000-foot (1,525-meter) mountain, local people said. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The quake struck the island's Oriental Mindaro province the day it planned to celebrate the 44th anniversary of its founding, and people planning a parade spent the day helping survivors. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 When the quake struck at 3:15 am, it was felt throughout the central and southern Philippines and rocked skyscrapers and tall hotels in Manila, 75 miles (120 kilometers) north of the epicenter. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 But no damage or injuries were reported very far outside the quake zone. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Throughout the day, several of the 888 aftershocks jarred Mindoro Island again, startling many residents. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 ``We are afraid of the sea,'' said Francisca Pascua, 48, as she walked toward two shelters that were quickly set up in a high school gym and on a hilly field near a hospital in the town of Calapan. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 She was with her four daughters and two grandchildren. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Many other shellshocked people also fled Malaylay, the hardest hit village, where at least 25 people died. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 For Purina Rosales, the nightmare began there when the quake leveled her bamboo home and the tidal wave struck. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 A few hours later, she found the bodies of Eduardo, her husband, and Alesa, her 4-year-old daughter, a long way away. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 ``I need you! 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 I need you!'' 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Mrs. Rosales screamed as she knelt in a one-room schoolhouse where they and 13 other bodies had been placed on benches. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 ``Why didn't you use your strength and swim?'' 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 she cried to her husband. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Like other survivors in the village of huts and dirt roads, Mrs. Rosales said she grabbed one of the area's many coconut trees when she was swept away by the tidal wave. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 In Malaylay and other fishing villages, several typhoons, including the strongest one last month, had kept many fishermen at home, but none of their homes was destroyed. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 That all changed Tuesday with the quake and tidal wave. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 President Fidel Ramos, who was at the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in Indonesia, sent dlrs 208,000 to help rebuild the homes. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Military helicopters also were rushing in food, drinking water and medical supplies. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The earthquake cut off electricity to most of Mindoro Island and destroyed many of its water mains, said Valencia. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 The quake had amgnitude of 7.1 and was centered in a strait six miles (10 kilometers) north of the island. 
apwsE9511250054-2-2-1 Ted Sandoval, a Filipino seismologist, said the temblor was one of the strongest ever to occur on the active Lubang fault. 
